{{Infobox language |name = Esselen |nativename = ''Huelel'' |states = [[United States|USA]] |region = [[Big Sur]] ([[California]]) |ethnicity=[[Esselen people|Esselen]] |extinct=19th century |familycolor = American |fam1=[[Hokan languages|Hokan]] ? |iso3 = esq |glotto = esse1238 |glottorefname= Esselen |map=Esselen lang.png |mapcaption= }}
'''Esselen''' was the language of the tiny [[Esselen]] (or self-designated ''Huelel'') Nation, which aboriginally occupied the mountainous [[Central Coast of California]], immediately south of [[Monterey, California|Monterey]] (Shaul 1995). It was probably a [[language isolate]], though has been included as a part of the hypothetical [[Hokan]] proposal.
Esselen may have been the first California language to become [[extinct language|extinct]]. Although it was spoken by many of the early converts at [[Mission Carmel]], its use rapidly declined during the Hispanic period. Very little information on the vocabulary and grammar of Esselen was preserved beyond a few word lists and a short bilingual catechism (for a summary see Mithun 1999:411–413 and Golla 2011:114). By the beginning of the 20th century the only data on Esselen that investigators such as [[Alfred L. Kroeber|Kroeber]] and [[John Peabody Harrington|Harrington]] could collect were a few words remembered by speakers of other Indian languages in the area.
