{{Infobox song | name = Have Some Madeira M'Dear | cover = File:Flanders and Swann At the Drop of a Hat Broadway.JPG | alt = Photo of Flanders and Swann singing at the piano | caption = Writers Flanders and Swann | type = song | artist = [[Flanders and Swann]] | album = | EP = | written = | published = | released = | format = | recorded = | studio = | venue = | genre = [[Novelty song]] | length = | label = | writer = | composer = [[Michael Flanders]] | lyricist = [[Donald Swann]] | producer = | prev_title = | prev_year = | title = | next_title = | next_year = | prev_track = | track_no = | next_track = }} '''"Have Some Madeira M'Dear"''', also titled "Madeira, M'Dear?",{{#tag:ref|The shorter title is used on the original LP records of the show; the longer is adopted in the 1977 collected songs of Flanders and Swann, edited by Flanders's widow Claudia.<ref>Parlophone LPs PMC 1033 (1957) and PCS 3001 (1959); and Flanders and Swann, p. 143</ref>|group= n}} is a [[Black humour|darkly comic]] song by [[Flanders and Swann]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Alcohol and temperance in modern history: an international encyclopedia, Volume 1 |last=Blocker |first=Jack S. |author2=[[David M. Fahey]] |author3=Ian R. Tyrrell |page=210 |year=2003 |publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]] |isbn=978-1-57607-833-4 }}</ref> It is a song about seduction and alcohol, containing complex and witty wordplay.
[[File:Madeira Barbeito Medium Dry Colheita-1999 Canteiro - Bottle + Glass.jpg|thumb|Madeira wine]] The [http://www.limeliters.net/have-some-madeira-mdear---lyrics.html lyrics]<ref>http://sniff.numachi.com/pages/tiMADERA.html</ref> tell of an elderly [[Rake (character)|rake]] who "slyly inveigles" an attractive young girl of seventeen to his flat where he offers her a glass of [[Madeira (wine)|Madeira]], a fortified Portuguese wine. The girl enthusiastically drains her glass, becoming slightly drunk in the process. Sensing victory, the rake offers the young girl another glass of wine, which she accepts. However, before raising it to her lips, she recalls her dying mother's warning to avoid red wine. With a cry, the girl drops the glass and flees the apartment, the old roué's pleas for her to remain echoing in her ears. The following morning, however, the young lady awakens in bed with a hangover and a beard tickling her ear.
The song contains three much-quoted instances of [[Zeugma#Syllepsis|syllepsis]]:<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Oliver | first1 = A. | title = Strategies for a Logic of Plurals | journal = [[The Philosophical Quarterly]] | volume = 51 | issue = 204 | pages = 289 | year = 2001 | doi = 10.1111/j.0031-8094.2001.00231.x}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Everett | first1 = Anthony | title = Recent Defenses of Descriptivism | journal = [[Mind & Language]] | volume = 20 | pages = 103 | year = 2005 | doi = 10.1111/j.0268-1064.2005.00279.x}}</ref> "And he said as he hastened to put out the cat, the wine, his cigar and the lamps" "She lowered her standards by raising her glass, her courage, her eyes and his hopes" "She made no reply, up her mind and a dash for the door."<ref name=fs>Flanders and Swann, pp. 143–145</ref>
The song has been covered by other groups, including most notably [[The Limeliters]] (performed by Lou Gottlieb). The lyrics were also recited as a poem by [[Tony Randall]] in episode #922 of ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]'' which first aired 02/21/1976.
[[Sam Leith]] has referred to it as a "hilarious song about [[date rape]]".<ref name=Leith>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=5sWVmvCEEnYC&pg=PA278&lpg=PA278&dq=%22have+some+madeira%22+rape&source=bl&ots=Uj75F0EszA&sig=MO2vtA0-so2D8EQhidpQaCymDCM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjm96eRg6DUAhWLzIMKHY3HAaMQ6AEITTAF#v=onepage&q=%22have%20some%20madeira%22e&f=false You Talkin' To Me?: Rhetoric from Aristotle to Obama], by [[Sam Leith]]; published Oct 20, 2011, by [[Profile Books]]; via [[Google Books]]</ref>
